# Assignment 2 – Detection and Retrieval Scripts

This folder contains two scripts:

- `run_detection.py`
- `retrieve.py`

Together, these implement the full image-to-video semantic retrieval pipeline.

The system first builds a detection index from video frames, then performs retrieval using a query image. Both scripts use the same trained YOLO model to ensure consistent semantic detection.

---

# `run_detection.py`

## What It Does

This script builds the video detection index.

It:

- Loads a trained YOLO model
- Runs detection on each sampled video frame
- Extracts bounding boxes
- Extracts class labels
- Extracts confidence scores
- Associates detections with timestamps
- Saves all detections to a Parquet file

Each row in the Parquet file represents one detected object in one frame.

## Example Command

```bash
python3 run_detection.py \
  --frames_dir frames \
  --video_id rav4_video \
  --seconds_per_frame 1 \
  --model runs/detect/train/weights/best.pt \
  --conf 0.35 \
  --out_parquet outputs/rav4_video_detections_carparts.parquet
```

## Output

The script produces a Parquet file containing:

- `video_id`
- `frame_index`
- `timestamp_sec`
- `class_label`
- `x_min`
- `y_min`
- `x_max`
- `y_max`
- `confidence_score`
- `model_name`

This file serves as the searchable semantic index for retrieval.

---

# `retrieve.py`

## What It Does

This script performs image-to-video retrieval using the detection index.

It:

- Loads a query image from the Hugging Face dataset
- Runs the same YOLO model on the query image
- Selects the highest-confidence detected class
- Filters the detection Parquet file for matching `class_label`
- Groups timestamps into contiguous segments
- Ranks segments by number of supporting detections
- Outputs video segments with YouTube verification links

## Example Command

```bash
python3 retrieve.py \
  --detections_parquet outputs/rav4_video_detections_carparts.parquet \
  --model runs/detect/train/weights/best.pt \
  --query_index 0 \
  --max_gap 10 \
  --top_k 10
```

## Retrieval Output

The script returns:

- `start_timestamp`
- `end_timestamp`
- `class_label`
- `number_of_supporting_detections`
- YouTube verification link

The `max_gap` parameter controls how nearby timestamps are merged into one continuous segment.  
The `top_k` parameter controls how many ranked segments are shown.
